{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698231/1937102201/0771.xml":{"full_text":"WASHINGTON FORECAST\nProbably rain, slightly colder tonight:\ntomorrow fair,' colder; moderate winds.\n(Details on Page 18.)\nNo. 17,555\nFire Destroys Big Baltimore Office Building\nRELIEF OUTLAY\nTO BE CURBED\nBY PRESIDENT\nWill Stay Inside 11\nBillion Fund\n(1.N.5.) President Roosevelt In\ntends to stay within the $1,500,-\n000,000 appropriated for Federal\nrelief during the current fiscal\nyear, he declared today.\nNo deficiency relief appropria\ntion will be asked of Congress for\n1937-38, he said.\nSEES BALANCED BUDGET\nMr. Roosevelt expressed con\ntinued confidence at his press con\nference today that the 1938-39\nbudget could be balanced despite\ndiscouraging revised estimates for\nthe current year.\nA reporter suggested he might\nbe getting reports from various\ndepartmental heads which could\nbe incorporated into a business\noutlook statement. Mr. Roosevelt\nreplied he did not have that in\nmind and felt publication of the\nregular departmental reports was\nsufficient to inform the country.\nTAX ACTION TO WAIT\nThe entire tax situation is now\nunder study by the Treasury De\npartment, the President said, and\nit is hoped Treasury experts will\nbe able to go before congressional\ncommittees during the November\nspecial session with reports.\nNo action on tax revision is con\ntemplated, however, until the reg\nular January session. The Presi\ndent parried questions about mod\nification of the undistributed\nprofits tax and the capital gains\ntax, saying the Treasury was\nstudying that problem along with\nothers. A final decision on a new\ntax setup has not yet been made,\nhe indicated.\nTO GO TO HYDE PARK\nBefore leaving Washington to\nmorrow afternoon for a two weeks\u2019\nstay at Hyde Park, Mr. Roose\nvelt said he planned to confer\nwith Budget Director Bell, Secre\ntary of Treasury Morgenthau, Sec.\nretary of Agriculture Wallace and\nSecretary of Labor Perkins about\nthe recommendations he will make\nto the special session on crop con\ntrol and hour-wage legislation.\nMartin and Lewis\nStudy Ford Drive\nDETROIT, Oct. 22 (1.N.5.).\nPresident Homer Martin, .of the\nC. I. O.\u2019s United Automobile Work\ners Uunion, was in Washington\ntoday to confer with Chieftain\nJohn L. Lewis on the campaign\nto organize Ford Motor Company\nworkers.\nYouth Crime Squad\nSought for Capital\nExtension of the Police Depart\nment\u2019s juvenile relations squad to\nhelp curb lawlessness among Wash\nington\u2019.- youth is recommended by\nthe Junior Board of Commerce and\nsocial service leaders.\nTIMES INDEX\nPage\nAndrew R. Kelley 32\nBill Corum 47\nBirths and Marriages 28\nBoake Carter 27\nComics 44, 45\nClassified Ads 49,50,51\nDrama 32,33\nEditorials 10\nEvalyn Walsh McLean...., 27\nFlora Macdonald 40\nFrank \u201cBuck\u201d O\u2019Neill 46\nHarry Costello 48\nHelen Essary 27\nInquiring Photographer 10\nJ. Earle Moser 11\nKirk Miller 46\nPaul Mallon 10\nPeter Carter i. 40\nRadio 29\nSociety 40, 42\nWomen\u2019s Clubs 41\nWomen\u2019s Page 38\nEntered Second C!m Matter at\nPoet Office at Washington, D. C.\nSweeps Draw Lifts\nHopes of 3 in D. C*\nLucky Ticket Holders'\nExcited by News\nHope beat high in the breasts\nof at least three Washingtonians\nand half a dozen residents of the\nWashington area today as draw\nings were announced for the Irish\nHospital Sweepstakes.\nMessages reaching Washington\ngave only the names of the horses\ndrawn, leaving the excited holders\nof lucky tickets on edge as they\nawaited further news as to what\ntheir horses are worth, if anything.\nHOPES IT\u2019S TRUE x\n\u201cI hope it\u2019s true,\u201d was the only\ncomment of Mrs. Daisy W. Russell\nof 2443 Eighteenth St. N. W.\nOne of the tickets is held by her\nhusband, Charles F. Russell, em\nployed in the Quartermaster de\npartment of the Army.\nMrs. Russell did not know\nwhether her husband was in the\nhabit of buying sweepstakes tickets,\nbut thought it was \u201cvery nice\u201d\nthat he has one now.\nHis horse is Irish Dream.\nMr. Russell was at Fort Myer\nwhen he heard the news.\n\u201cThat\u2019s an awfully good\nname!\u201d he said. \u201cI\u2019m Irish my\nself and know I\u2019ll win some\nthing. All the horse, has to do\nis to start. I don\u2019t know much\nabout Irish Dream. He\u2019s prob\nably a \u2018nickel horse,\u2019 no more\nthan a 100-to-l shot.\u201d\nAnother Washingtonian whose\nname appears in the list of ticket\nholders as received here today\nfrom New York is C. P. Bryant,\n473 H St. N. W. His horse is Near\nRelation, listed as the second fa\nvorite in the race. If Near Rela\ntion should win, Bryant would\nreceive $150,000.\n\"NEVER CLOSE\u201d\nO. V. Keele, a pressman at the\nGovernment Printing Office, was\naroused from bed at his home,\n2111 Fourth St. N. E., to learn\nhe was among the lucky.\n\u201cThat\u2019s good,\u201d he said sleepily.\n\u201cI hope he wins.\u201d\n\u201cEver buy tickets before?\u201d\n\u201cThousands of \u2019em! On every\nthing!\u201d\n\u201cEver draw a horse?\u201d\n\u201cNever even came close.\u201d\nHis ticket was bought in partner\nship with a \u201cfriend of mine\u201d\nnamed Fisher, but Mr. Keele said\nhe could not identify him further.\n\u201cHe works in a hardware\nstore,\u201d he said, \u201cbut I don\u2019t\nknow his initials and I don\u2019t\nknow where he lives\u2014and that\u2019s\nthe truth.\u201d\nTheir horse is Dytchley.\nTHE WINNERS\nThese are among the lucky Americans who drew tickets on\nfavorites in the Irish Sweepstakes:\nC. P. Bryant, 473 H St.\nS. W.\nKeele and Fisher, 2114\nFourth St. N. E.\nCharles F. Russell, 2443\nEighteenth St. N. W.\nToots Brill and Leslie Saun\nders, Alexandria, Va.\nE. Doswell, Richmond, Va,\nGo Boy, Richmond, Va.\nT. F. Downs, Richmond,\nVa.\nR. J. Ruffin, Richmond,\nVa.\nJoseph R. Lynch, North\nEast, Md.\nOthers include:\nD. Koleda, Pittsburgh.\nConcetta and Parisina\nNielli, Brooklyn, N. Y.\nLucy Pohlman, New York\ncity.\nFrank M. Gray, East\nOrange.\nLouis Stomato, Philadel\nphia.\nF. M. Percy, Chicago.\n\u201cNever It or Never Will,\u201d\nBronx, N. Y.\nNEWS PAP ED J\u2014 JL J\u2014J -H\nbi\nw t 11\nSO y'R\n11\npj\n\nI\nCHARLES F. RUSSELL\nIIHUDRAW\nRACE FAVORITE\nDUBLIN, Oct. 22 (I.N.S.).\u2014With\nthe possibility of winning $150,000\napiece, seven lucky Americans\ndrew tickets on the outstanding\nfavorite, Epigram, in the Irish Hos\npitals Sweepstakes draw on the\nCesare witch today. They are:\n\u201cNever It or Never Will,\" Bronx,\nN. Y.\nGrand Manitou, Los Angeles.\nGustavo Cianfrocca, East Bos\nton, Mass.\nTry Again, U. S. S. New Mexico,\nSan Pedro, Cal.\nLady Lead, Eggertsville, N. Y.\nSix and Seven-eighths, 1137 Alli\nson St. N. W., Washington. D. C.\nTwinsy Kitten, Forest Hills, L. I.\nAt the first recess Americans\nheld 101 of the first 180 winning\ntickets. The United States held\n10 winners each on April the\nThird, Incantator, Stainless\nStephen and Black Fell.\nThe luncheon recess found 329\nout of 600 winning tickets in\nAmerican hands. The American\npercentage went to a new high\nwhen 12 out of the 15 prizes on\nDytchley. an outsider, went to the\nUnited States.\nEight Americans drew Miss\nWindsor, nine drew Signature and\nseven drew Lagopeda, promising a\nnew record in the proportion of\nriches that will go to the United\nStates, estimated at 50 per cent of\nthe total.\nGrand Manitou, Los An\ngeles.\nGustavo Cianfrocca, East\nBoston, Mass.\nTry Again, U. S. S. New\nMexico, San Pedro, Cal.\nLady Lead, Eggertsville,\nN. Y.\nSix and Seven-eighths,\u201d\n1137 Allison St. N. W., Wash\nington, D. C.\nTwinsy Kitten, Forest Hills,\nL. I.\nLeague o's Nations Can\u2019t\nLose, Brooklyn.\nWe Need It, Brooklyn.\nJohn A. Preischel, Buffalo,\nN. Y.\nGood News, Los Angeles.\nRalph Frazese, Long Island,\nN. Y.\nBob Green, San Jose, Cal.\nJust Plain Bill Bloosburg,\nTioga county, Pennsylvania.\nPearl and June Schultz,\nOak Lawn, Cook county, Illi\nnois.\nFRIDAY, OCTOBER 22, 1937\n30 ARE KILLED\nIN U. S. ZONE\nAT SHANGHAI\n500,000 Troops In\nTerrific Battle\nSHANGHAI, Oct. 22 (IN.S.).\nThirty persons were killed today,\nand 50 Chinese were wounded\nwhen a bomb fell into the Ameri\ncan defense sector of the inter\nnational settlement during a Japa\nnese bombardment of Chapel, just\nto the north.\nThe explosion occurred while\nAmerican and other western troops\nmanned the settlement\u2019s barri\ncades as 300,000 Chinese troops\nclashed with 200,000 Japanese in\na terrific battle just north of the\ncity.\nU. S. MARINE BURNED\nThe bomb fell in the American\nsector near Suchow Creek as the\nJapanese poured missels into the\nravaged Chapel area.\nUnited States Marine Sergeant\nJohn R. Coleman was burned on\nthe hands as he went to the as\nsistance of a Chinese woman\nwhose clothing had been set on\nfire by the blast. Coleman\u2019s home\nIs in Atkins, Ark.\nMajor General Beaumont. Amer\nican commander, immediately pro\ntested to Admiral Hasegawa, high\nest ranking Japanese official in\nthe Shanghai war zone. The ad\nmiral expressed \"sincere regrets\"\nand promised to prevent a recur\nrence of the explosion, which oc\ncurred at the comer of Myburgh\nand Sinza Roads.\nPROTESTS REITERATED\nFour Sihks and 25 Chinese were\ntaken to hospitals suffering from\nburns caused by the bomb.\nThe incident followed repeated\nprotests by American authorities\nhere and at Nanking to both\nChinese and Japanese officials\nagainst military activities endang\nering the settlement.\nMeanwhile, from Peiping came\nadvices that Japanese forces had\nbroken Chinese resistance after\nhand-to-hand fighting in the Hsin\nkow Mountains of Shansi prov\nince, and it was expected the Nip\nponese drive toward Taiyuanfu\nwould be speeded up.\nROUTED FROM TRENCHES\nThese reports stated the Jap\nanese advanced against machine\ngun and rifle fire and a hail of\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 2)\nEleanor Holm Can\u2019t\nBe Bothered Now\nHOLLYWOOD, Oct. 22 (1.N.5.).\nEleanor Holm Jarrett, the cham\npion swimmer who turned actress,\ncontinued her work in the studios\nhere today, quite unmindful of\nthe fact that her husband, Art\nJarrett, band leader, plans a Texas\ndivorce,\n\u201cI\u2019d get it, if he would wait\nuntil I am through with this\npicture,\u201d she said.\nShe added that she and Jarrett\nagreed to part several months ago.\nLady Hamilton\nTo Christen Ship\nBERLIN, Oct. 22 (1.N.5.) .\u2014Lady\nHamilton, wife of the London\nrepresentative of the standard Oil\nCompany of California, tomorrow\nwill christen the company\u2019s 17,150\nton oil tanker China, it was an\nnounced today.\nThe vessel, built at Kiel, is\ndestined for San Francisco.\n3 RUSSIANS EXECUTED\nMOSCOW, Oct. 22 (1.N.5.).\nThree more persons were executed\nat Kharbarovsk today for sabotage.\nJapanese \u201cSuicide Corps\u201d in Action\na\ni\n\nI\n1|\nBwr J itw\nwi- aIHK fl Vwi?\nB AC\nInternational News Photo\nWHILE SMOKE from Japanese bombs\nstill lingers in the air, a detachment of\nNippon\u2019s \u201cdeath volunteers,\u201d who indicate\ntheir willingness to die by wearing white\nSTOCKS SLUMP,\nTHEN REBOUND\nNEW yORK, Oct. 22 (1.N.5.).\nThe profit-taking urge dominated\nan erratic stock market from the\nopening day. This brought a\nflurry of heavy selling which at\none time saw leading issues off $1\nto $3 from last night's close.\nSupport then appeared and a\nlarge part of the losses were re\ncovered. Trading was heavy for a\nwhile, the ticker falling two min\nutes behind, but turnover con\ntinued to contract from the huge\nvolume since Tuesday.\nSteels and rails were the reac\ntions leaders, the latter influenced\nby failure of the rumored I. C. C.\nfreight rate decision to develop\novernight. Declines in rails ran\nto nearly $3 a share in Atchison\nbut these were largely erased by\nthe second hour and, in some cases,\nsmall gains substituted.\nU. S. Steel fell nearly $3 and\nthen worked back toward the pre\nvious close. Chrysler wiped out a\n$2 loss, and elsewhere the same\ntrend prevailed.\nVon Ribbentrop\nArrives in Rome\nROME, Oct. 22 (I.N.S.).\u2014Ac\ncompanied by his wife and daugh\nter, Joachim Von Ribbentrop, Ger\nman ambassador to England, ar\nrived here today from Berlin. His\ntrip was said to be primarily to\nobtain expert medical attention\nfor his daughter, recently injured\nin an automobile accident, but he\nis expected to discuss with For\neign Minister Ciano careful joint\nItalo-German procedure regarding\nthe future of Spanish non-inter\nvention.\nbands, rushes into a ruined building to\n\u201cclean it up\u201d after the bombing by killing\nChinese snipers within. Note man falling\nat the right.\nHitler Is Host\nTo Windsors\nIn Villa\nBERCHTESGADEN, Germany,\nOct. 22 (1.N.5.). \u2014The man who\nrenounced a throne for love and\nthe Austrian who remade the Ger\nman republic met for the first time\ntoday.\nAccompanied by his American\nborn duchess, the Duke of Wind\nsor came to Berchtesgaden from\nI Stuttgart and spent more than\ntwo hours with Reichsfuehrer Adolf\nHitler at his villa, Haus Wachen\nfels, in the Bavarian Alps.\nA cavalcade of five cars brought\nthe Windsors up the winding road\nto the fuehrer\u2019s rustic villa,\nperched on a cliff.\n(1.N.5.) The Duke and Duchess\nI of Windsor may be coming to this\ncountry, but so far as any com\nmunication is concerned President\nRoosevelt doesn\u2019t know about it.\nHe was asked today at his press\nconference whether the Duke and\nhis American bride had commu\nnicated with the White House.\nSmiling broadly, the President said\nnothing had been received.\n\u2018Ads\u2019 on Pyramids,\nMovie King\u2019s Plan\nHOLLYWOOD, Oct. 22 (1.N.5.). Producer Sam Goldwyn\nnever misses a trick, as they say in Hollywood.\nHearing reports that the Egyp-'\ntian government had planned to\nlease the sides of the historic pyra\nmids for advertising purposes, he\nhad his advertising manager send\na cablegram today asking permis\nsion to utilize the opportunity to\nHOME\nE DITI ON\nCHAMPIONS VIE\nIN HORSE SHOW\nBy HARRY COSTELLO\nReduce an international compe\ntition to the individual represen\ntative of one nation pitted against\nthe indivdual of another nation\nand you have a magnet which will\nattract a crowd.\nIt was thus when Dempsey\nfought Carpentier, and Firpo. It\nwas thus when Walter Hagen met\nTed Ray in golf. It was thus when\nTilden met Cochet across a tennis\nnet. It\u2019s thus today, at the Inter-\nAmerican Horse Show. Meadow\nbrook Saddle Club in Rock Creek\nPark at the East-West Highway,\nfor today\u2014the second day of the\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 3)\nRush Seen to Beat\nWedding Test Law\nLANSING, Mich., Oct. 22\n(I.N.S.).\u2014A rush on marriage li\nj cense bureaus was anticipated in\nMichigan today after Attorney\nGeneral Starr announced the new\ncompulsory physical examination\nilaw will go into effect tonight.\nadvertise one of his forthcoming\npictures.\n\u201cThis company would con\nsider utilizing this opportunity\nin a dignified manner,\u201d said\nthe message.\nTHREE CENTS\nGAS COMPANY\u2019S\nOFFICE TOTAL\nLOSS IN BLAZE\n60 Employes Flee\nVast Inferno\nBALTIMORE, Md., Oct. 22.\nParalyzing traffic for blocks, fire\nbroke out in the Baltimore Gas\nlight Company\u2019s show rooms in the\nheart of this city today and com\npletely destroyed the building be\nfore firemen could get the blaze\nunder control.\nSixty employes were at work\nwhen the fire was discovered at\n10:30 o'clock this morning.\nSaid to have started from the\nfourth floor, it spread so rapidly\nthat within 10 minutes the whole\nfive-story building was in flames.\nEmployes were hustled to the\nstreet as the alarm rang out.\nFiremen, finding their ladders\nwould not stand the heat of the\nwalls, were forced to retreat to\na safer distance. Seven alarms\nwere sounded and the fire raged\nuntil finally the entire inside of\nthe building was destroyed.\nEvery street within a wide ra\ndius of Lombard and Calvert,\nwhere the building is located, was\nblocked.\nThousands of dollars worth of\nelectrical appliances were reported\nlost in addition to the damage\ndone to the building.\nMurray to Wed\nGirl From N.Y.U.\nHOLLYWOOD, Cal., October 22\n(C.T.P.S.).\u2014Around the first of\nthe year, Ken Murray, radio and\nscreen player, and Miss Florence\nI Heller, of New York University,\nwill be married, Ken admits. The\nbride-to-be is en route East to pre\npare her trousseau. Miss Heller,\nwho has played two years of stock,\nis the daughter of Mrs. George\nHeller, of New York, and the niece\nof Col. Joseph Heller, retired.\nCrash Sinks Barge;\nOne Known Victim\nBAYONNE, N. J., Oct. 22 1.N.5.)\nOne man was drowned today and\nan undetermined number were\nmissing when the barge Nancy\nLee sank in the Kill Van Kull\nafter a crash with the S. S. Moore\nand McCormack, a freighter. The\nbarge, loaded with 80,000 gallons\nof fuel oil, sank almost immedi\nately.\nContract Granted\nFor Safety Liner\n<I.N.S.) Contract for a new\nmodel safety liner to replace the\nLeviathan in the North Atlantia\nservice was awarded today to the\nNewport News Shipbuilding and\nDrydock Company of Newport\nNews, Va., which bid $15,750,000,\nlow of three submitted. The award\nwas signed by Chairman Kennedy\nof the Maritime Commission.\nUSED CARS\nwith that new car\nperformance\nThis is one of the best\ntimes to purchase a good\nUsed Car\nMake your choice easier\nby relying on the large\nselection on the Classified\nPages in today's\nTIMES.","height":"25792","width":"20214"}}
